Part I - (Exploration on the FordGoBike Dataset )¶

by (Christopher Ohwavworua)¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. It covers the detais of 183412 rides observed in 16 different columns. These details include the duration of rides in seconds, the statr and end time of rides,the stsrt and end station names, the geographical positions of the start and end stations, the year of birth of riders, the sex of the riders, and the user type of the riders.

Data quality¶

  1. Missing data in the following columns(start_station_name,end_station_name,member_gender,member_birth_year)
  2. Data type format for start_time and end_time set as Object
  3. Start and end station id to be deleted
  4. vauge column name duration_sec
  5. outliers observed in member age distribution.
  6. outliers observed in the bike ride duration distribution.

Data Cleaning¶

Define¶

  1. Droping all missing data in the following columns(start_station_name,end_station_name,member_gender,member_birth_year)
  2. Coverting data type for start_time and end_time to datetime type and bike id to objects
  3. Droping all columns not relevant for our analysis.
  4. Changing the name of column for clarity
  5. droping records where member age is greater than 80
  6. droping records where bike duration exceeds 120 mins
  7. Creating cloumns such as start day of week, start date of the week and start hour of the day.
  8. converting the measure of duration of bike ride to minutes

Code¶

# Changing the data type for start_time, end_time and bike id

df['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['end_time'], format = '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')
df['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['start_time'], format = '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')
df['bike_id'] = df['bike_id'].astype(str)

In [234]:
# droping all Nan values in the following columns(start_station_name,end_station_name,member_gender,member_birth_year)

df.dropna(inplace = True)
In [235]:
# Creating a new column for member age and droping the column for member birth year.
df['member_age'] = df['member_birth_year'].apply(lambda x: 2022-x).astype("int64")
In [236]:
# droping records where member age is greater than 80
filt = df['member_age'] > 80
df.drop(index = df.loc[filt].index,inplace = True)
In [237]:
#Converting time duration measured in sec to minutes
df['ride_duration_in_mins'] = df['duration_sec'].apply(lambda x: x/60).round(2)
In [238]:
# droping records where bike ride duration greater than 120
timefilt = df['ride_duration_in_mins']>120
df.drop(index = df.loc[timefilt].index,inplace = True)
In [239]:
# creating new columns for Day_of_week and date
df['Start_date'] = df['start_time'].dt.strftime('%d')
df['Hour_of_day'] = df['start_time'].dt.strftime('%H')
df['day_of_week']= df['start_time'].dt.day_name()

# Creating a function that to set labels and titles

def label(x,y,t):
    """
    Args:
    x(str): 'x-axis title'
    y(str): 'y-axis title'
    t(str): 'main title'
    Returns:
    None

    """
    plt.xlabel(x,fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
    plt.ylabel(y,fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
    plt.title(t,fontsize = 15, weight = 'bold')
In [247]:
# Creating a function for my count plots

def myCountPlot(df_clean,xVar):
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    asc = df_clean[xVar].value_counts().index
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
    sb.countplot(data=df_clean,x= xVar,color=base_color,order=asc)
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {xVar}'''.title(), fontsize = 14, weight = 'bold')
    plt.xlabel(xVar.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency'.title(),fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There was an unusual observations on the member age distribution. It was observed that some persons that had the bike ride were over a hundred years old. In reality, this is practically impossible as i suspect that errors were made while capturing the year of birth data. So for all riders that were above 80 years their records were deleted.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The relationship between the gender type and the bike ride duration was one that supports the general saying that females are the weaker gender physically. It showed that the mean period for ride completing for females was greater than that of the males. Alternatively, it could be said that the males spend lesser time completing their rides. Also the count of bike rides per day of week revealed that the weekends(saturdays and sundays) do not really command much traffic as regards bike rides. This could also suggest that economic activities during weekends in sanfrancisco is relatively low when compared to week days.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The relationship between the frequency of bike rides for customers and subcribers over the week is one that requires a further investigation. From the chart, an almost even frequency of bike rides was observed for custpomers while there was a very significant observation of frequency variation per week day.
